A company's application uses Network Load Balancers, Auto Scaling groups, Amazon EC2 instances, and databases that are deployed in an Amazon VPC. The company wants
to capture information about traffic to and from the network interfaces in near real time in its Amazon VPC. The company wants to send the information
to Amazon OpenSearch Service for analysis.

Which solution will meet these requirements?

A. Create a log group in Amazon CloudWatch Logs. Configure VPC Flow Logs to send the log data to the log group. Use Amazon Kinesis Data Streams to 
stream the logs from the log group to OpenSearch Service.
B. Create a log group in Amazon CloudWatch Logs. Configure VPC Flow Logs to send the log data to the log group. Use Amazon Kinesis Data Firehose to
stream the logs from the log group to OpenSearch Service. Most Voted
C. Create a trail in AWS CloudTrail. Configure VPC Flow Logs to send the log data to the trail. Use Amazon Kinesis Data Streams to stream the logs 
from the trail to OpenSearch Service.
D. Create a trail in AWS CloudTrail. Configure VPC Flow Logs to send the log data to the trail. Use Amazon Kinesis Data Firehose to stream the logs 
from the trail to OpenSearch Service.



CloudTrail is for logging administrative actions, we need CloudWatch. We want the data in another AWS service (OpenSearch),
not Kinesis, thus we need Firehose, not Streams.

Amazon CloudWatch Logs and VPC Flow Logs (Option B): VPC Flow Logs capture information about the IP traffic going to and from network interfaces in a VPC



AWS provides CloudWatch and CloudTrail as monitoring and logging services, but they serve different purposes.

Feature	           Amazon CloudWatch	                                      AWS CloudTrail
Purpose	           Monitors AWS resources & applications in real time	     Tracks API activity & user actions in AWS
Use Case	           Performance monitoring, metrics, logs, and alerts	     Security auditing, compliance, and API call tracking
What It Tracks	     - Metrics (CPU, memory, latency, network, etc.)          - AWS Management Console logins
                    - Logs (errors, events, app logs)                        - API calls (who did what, when, and from where)
                    - Dashboards & alarms	                                   - Changes to AWS resources (EC2, S3, IAM, etc.)
Data Type	        Real-time performance data and logs	                    Event history of API activity
Example Uses	     - Monitor EC2 CPU usage                                  - Track who deleted an S3 bucket
                    - Set alarms for high memory usage                       - Detect unauthorized access to AWS
                    - View application logs	                                - Audit changes to IAM policies
Retention Period	  Varies based on logs & metrics storage settings	        90 days by default (longer if stored in S3)
Integration         Works with EC2, RDS, Lambda, EKS, etc.	                 Works with AWS services that use API calls

